// src/pages/commercial/range-repair/restaurant-range-salamander-repair.astro
// Phase B-7 — Restaurant Range with Salamander Broiler Repair sub-service.
// Premium niche, declined by most LA shops = practitioner moat.
// $120 commercial diagnostic. BHGS #A49573, EPA 608 #1346255700410, .
// Em-dash budget: visible body ≤2.

import Layout from '../../../layouts/Layout.astro';
import CommercialHero from '../../../components/CommercialHero.astro';
import { MAIN_PHONE } from '../../../data/branches';

const phone = MAIN_PHONE;
const phoneRaw = MAIN_PHONE.replace(/\D/g, '');
const phoneHref = `tel:+1${phoneRaw}`;
const canonical = "https://samedayappliance.repair/commercial/range-repair/restaurant-range-salamander-repair/";

const title = "Commercial Range Salamander Repair Los Angeles — Same Day";
const description = "Restaurant range salamander broiler repair across LA, OC, Ventura. Vulcan, Garland, Imperial. Premium niche specialists. BHGS #A49573. $120 dx.";

const faqs = [
  {
    q: "What is a salamander broiler and why is it integrated with the range?",
    a: "Salamander equals a high-heat finishing broiler mounted above the range top, designed for finishing dishes (cheese melt, browning, finishing steaks). Reaches 800 to 1,200°F at the broiler grate. Restaurant chefs use the salamander for the final 30 to 60 second finish on plated dishes. Integrated salamander on a range gives the cook line one continuous workstation, the salamander is positioned for the chef to slide a plate or pan from the range surface directly under the broiler without moving stations. Heavy-duty restaurant ranges (Vulcan VR-60, Wolf Challenger XL CHSC60, Garland US-Range U Series) commonly include salamander integration."
  },
  {
    q: "Why do most LA appliance shops decline salamander work?",
    a: "Three reasons. (1) Specialty equipment, fewer trained techs in the LA market because the volume doesn't justify investment in salamander-specific training for most shops. (2) Heavy-duty heat exposure means salamander burner heads, igniters, and grates wear faster than range components, more frequent failure modes that shops without specialty knowledge misdiagnose. (3) Premium tier customer base (Beverly Hills steakhouses, Bel Air private dining, Hollywood premium restaurants) has white-glove service expectations that smaller shops can't meet. We service salamanders routinely, the niche fits our practitioner model."
  },
  {
    q: "My salamander burner head is deformed. Replace or refurbish?",
    a: "Replace. Salamander burner heads are exposed to 800 to 1,200°F continuously during service, far higher thermal stress than range burners (which see 600 to 800°F maximum). When the burner head deforms, gas distribution becomes uneven, broil pattern goes off, and the deformation accelerates. Refurbishing isn't practical (industrial-trade specialty, costs more than replacement). Replacement runs $480 to $720 typical. We carry common Vulcan VR-60 salamander burner heads on the truck."
  },
  {
    q: "Do you handle LA pre-fire permit documentation for salamander installations?",
    a: "We don't issue permits, that's city / county jurisdiction. But we frequently encounter operators whose salamander installations don't have updated pre-fire permits, especially after an installation date several years ago. We document equipment, model numbers, and installation context at every service call so the operator has the records when permitting questions come up. For new permit submissions or updates, we coordinate with installer trade or directly with the operator's facility manager. It matters because LA fire marshal inspections sometimes flag undocumented salamander installs."
  },
  {
    q: "How often do salamander igniters fail compared to range burner igniters?",
    a: "Faster. Salamander igniters typically fail at year 3 to 5 vs year 4 to 7 on range burners. Higher heat exposure plus more frequent ignition cycles (chefs ignite the salamander every service, sometimes multiple times per shift) accelerate electrode wear. We replace as paired set with thermocouple when both are within their respective wear windows; mismatched replacement creates callback risk in 6 to 12 months."
  },
  {
    q: "Vulcan VR-60 with salamander vs Wolf Challenger XL CHSC60 with salamander, which is better?",
    a: "Both are excellent. Vulcan VR-60 (ITW Food Equipment Group) has the broader LA install base and faster parts pipeline. Wolf Challenger XL CHSC60 (Wolf Industrial / Sub-Zero Group commercial) has heavier-duty stainless construction and slightly better salamander broil pattern at extreme high heat. Both are repairable through year 18+ with proper salamander-specific maintenance. Garland US-Range U Series sits between the two with comparable build and proven LA serviceability."
  },
  {
    q: "What's your warranty?",
    a: "90 days SDAR labor warranty on every repair. Component manufacturer warranties (Vulcan, Wolf Industrial, Garland US-Range, Montague) processed separately through the manufacturer's authorized network. BHGS #A49573. EPA 608 Universal certified (#1346255700410).  scope. BBB A+ accredited."
  }
];

